comments.message:
I think this function usage seems overloaded, and can be divided into 2 functions, and use them accordingly.

1)
```
// Check whether conn is active
inline bool checkConnection(crow::websocket::Connection& conn)
{
   return !(sessions.find(&conn)== sessions.end());
}

```

2)
```
// remove the connection if it is connected
inline bool eraseConnection(crow::websocket::Connection& conn)
{
  if(!checkConnection(conn))
  {
          BMCWEB_LOG_ERROR << "Couldn't find the connection";
  }
  else       
  {
          sessions.erase(&conn);
        if (sessions.empty())
        {
            hostSocket = nullptr;
            inputBuffer.clear();
            inputBuffer.shrink_to_fit();
        }
   }
}
```

Perhaps, similar to .onclose() case.
what if a trace goes inside lambda here like

```
.onopen([](crow::websocket::Connection& conn) {
        BMCWEB_LOG_DEBUG << "Connection " << &conn << " opened";
        openConnection(conn);
        })
```

Is this always returning 'true'?
What if 'conn' was already removed before removeConnection() is called?

Should it be like?

```
 if( sessions.erase(&conn) == sessions.end() )
 { 
    return false;
 }
 ...
```
